orida confirms Burmese python breeding hotspot outside the Everglades, and wildlife experts fear it could be the start of a bigger spread]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132528814.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/florida-confirms-burmese-python-breeding-hotspot-outside-the-everglades-and-wildlife-experts-fear-it-could-be-the-start-of-a-bigger-spread/articleshow/132528814.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/rest-of-world/florida-confirms-burmese-python-breeding-hotspot-outside-the-everglades-and-wildlife-experts-fear-it-could-be-the-start-of-a-bigger-spread/articleshow/132528814.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-21T11:30:00+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI World Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132528864,imgsize-285045.cms"/></item><item><title><![CDATA[Pollution drains energy from Hawaii corals, worsening survival in warming seas]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132532531.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[Human chemicals are accumulating inside coral tissues, weakening their ability to cope.  Contaminants from various sources build up, reducing vital nutrient and energy reserves.  This internal chemical shift makes corals significantly less resilient to environmental stressors.  Monitoring these internal chemical fingerprints offers a new way to track hidden impacts.  Reducing chemical pollution is crucial for protecting marine and human health.]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/science/hawaiis-corals-were-exposed-to-polluted-water-and-lost-energy-needed-to-survive-warming-seas-with-the-same-damage-seen-in-two-very-different-species/articleshow/132532531.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/science/hawaiis-corals-were-exposed-to-polluted-water-and-lost-energy-needed-to-survive-warming-seas-with-the-same-damage-seen-in-two-very-different-species/articleshow/132532531.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-21T14:57:55+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI Science Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132532572,imgsize-242144.cms"/></item><item><title><![CDATA[Rare Woodhouse's Toad returns after 65 years, caught calling for a mate]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132529931.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[A rare Woodhouse's toad has been spotted at Las Vegas' Springs Preserve for the first time in nearly 65 years. The male was recorded making a mating call in the restored wetland, marking the species' first confirmed return since the original springs dried up around 1962. Conservationists have called the sighting an important moment for local wildlife, while the public has joined in by suggesting names for the lone visitor.]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/science/a-rare-woodhouses-toad-has-returned-to-las-vegas-springs-preserve-for-the-first-time-in-nearly-65-years-where-cameras-caught-a-lone-male-calling-for-a-mate/articleshow/132529931.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/science/a-rare-woodhouses-toad-has-returned-to-las-vegas-springs-preserve-for-the-first-time-in-nearly-65-years-where-cameras-caught-a-lone-male-calling-for-a-mate/articleshow/132529931.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-21T14:55:00+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI Science Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132530735,imgsize-195082.cms"/></item><item><title><![CDATA[Bill Koch's magnificent Aspen estate, originally listed at $125 million, now draws buyers with $33.515 million price tag]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132532389.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[Billionaire Bill Koch's expansive Aspen estate has sold for $33.515 million after a luxury auction.  The property, initially listed at $125 million, struggled to find a buyer for two years.  After several price reductions, the 52-acre Elk Mountain Lodge went to a competitive bidding process.  This sale highlights shifts in the ultra-luxury housing market and buyer selectivity.  The transaction represents a notable luxury home sale in Aspen this year.]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/real-estate/news/billionaire-bill-kochs-52-acre-aspen-estate-once-asked-125-million-but-after-price-cuts-and-an-auction-it-is-poised-to-sell-for-33-515-million/articleshow/132532389.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/real-estate/news/billionaire-bill-kochs-52-acre-aspen-estate-once-asked-125-million-but-after-price-cuts-and-an-auction-it-is-poised-to-sell-for-33-515-million/articleshow/132532389.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-21T14:47:00+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI Real Estate Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132532420,imgsize-167081.cms"/></item></channel></rss>